    "answer": "Single sample t-tests, paired t-tests, independent t-tests, ANOVA, and regression are statistical methods used for different purposes. Single sample t-tests assess if a sample mean differs from a known population mean, useful for testing standards or treatment effects. Paired t-tests compare means of two related samples, such as pre- and post-treatment measurements. Independent t-tests compare means of two independent groups, like different demographic groups or treatment groups. ANOVA compares means across three or more groups to find significant differences, applicable in multi-group comparisons like drug effectiveness. Regression models relationships between a dependent variable and one or more independent variables, used for predictions and understanding causality, such as predicting house prices or examining income-education relationships. Each method has specific assumptions and data requirements, guiding their appropriate use in statistical analysis."
